        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer167129689" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10378372908276065611">This is why I love Julia Quinn books: I laughed, I cried, and then I laughed so hard I cried.<br/><br/>As always, the dedication to her husband is worth the price of admission alone. I won&apos;t spoil that for you. ;)<br/><br/>On p. 57 (of this edition), was the first bit that made me laugh out loud: <blockquote>
  <i>And Honoria had a plan. It wasn&apos;t terribly complicated; she needed only a sunny day, a halfway acceptable sense of direction, and a shovel.</i>
</blockquote><br/>It was 11 pages later that we found out what she was up to. And 10 pages after </span>
  <span id="freeText10378372908276065611" style="display:none">This is why I love Julia Quinn books: I laughed, I cried, and then I laughed so hard I cried.<br /><br />As always, the dedication to her husband is worth the price of admission alone. I won't spoil that for you. ;)<br /><br />On p. 57 (of this edition), was the first bit that made me laugh out loud: <blockquote>
  <i>And Honoria had a plan. It wasn't terribly complicated; she needed only a sunny day, a halfway acceptable sense of direction, and a shovel.</i>
</blockquote><br />It was 11 pages later that we found out what she was up to. And 10 pages after that when it all goes horribly, horribly wrong. (Of course!)<br /><br />The ensuing blend of tragedy and comedy includes such gems as: <blockquote>
  <i>Or maybe he still was in hell, although if so, the beds were certainly comfortable. Which certainly did seem to contradict everything he'd learned in church.</i>
</blockquote><br />Then there was the bit about the dream/hallucination featuring a giant rabbit. With a giant, mace-like carrot.<br /><br />The discussion about touchstones got me all teary. But not as teary as the very end . . .<br /><br />And the cousins bickering while practicing for the quartet was simply hilarious.</span>
  <a data-text-id="10378372908276065611" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
